The unified read and write ay-pee-eye.

Spark reads and writes data through a single fluent ay-pee-eye. For input, you write spark dot read, then dot format with the format name in quotes, then any options, then dot load with a path. For output, df dot write, then dot format, then dot mode for the write mode, then dot save with a path. Same shape, just different format strings.

The format-shorthand methods — dot c-s-v, dot json, dot parquet, dot orc — are aliases for the longer form. Same plumbing, less typing.

Five formats matter for everyday Spark work.

C-s-v, comma-separated values. Schema comes from the header row or an explicit declaration. Best for human-readable text. Slow.

JSON, with the schema either inferred or declared. Best for semi-structured payloads — loan-origination records, ay-pee-eye dumps.

Parquet, columnar binary. Schema is embedded in the file footer. The default for analytics workloads.

ORC — short for optimized row columnar — also columnar binary, common in legacy hadoop pipelines. Same mental model as parquet.

Delta — schema embedded plus a transaction log. The lakehouse storage format. Adds acid transactions and time travel on top of parquet.

Setup.

The data folder is generated by generate-bank-data — see the apache-spark CLAUDE file for details. Eight tables across five formats — c-s-v, json, parquet, orc, and delta — all matching the canonical schemas in the project schemas folder.

All write examples in this notebook land in data slash underscore write examples, so the source data stays untouched.

In code, build a spark session with the delta config, set a warehouse directory at data slash underscore warehouse — we use that later for save as table — make sure both directories exist, and list the data folder contents to confirm the eight tables are there.

Reading the five formats.

One inline cell per format, each reading a real bank table from the data folder.

C-s-v, the customers table. The header-equals-true option reads the first row as column names. Always pass an explicit schema in production — inference is slow and can guess wrong.

In code, declare the customers schema as a struct type with ten struct fields — customer ID, full name, email, phone, date of birth, gender, city, state, country, and a created-at timestamp. Then call spark dot read, set the schema, set header to true, set the separator to comma — that is the default, but explicit reads better — and call dot c-s-v with the customers folder path. Show three rows and the row count.

JSON, the card-accounts table. Each line is one JSON object, the line-delimited form. Use the multi-line option set to true if each record spans multiple lines.

In code, declare the card-accounts schema with six struct fields, including a decimal type for credit limit. Then spark dot read dot schema dot json with the path. Three rows shown.

Parquet, the card-transactions table. Parquet embeds its schema in the file footer, so Spark reads it automatically. Passing an explicit schema is still useful — you can enforce types or select a column subset, and then predicate-and-projection pushdown read less data off disk.

In code, just spark dot read dot parquet with the folder path. Print the schema, show three rows, print the row count.

ORC, the bank-accounts table. Same mental model as parquet — columnar binary with embedded schema. Common in legacy hadoop pipelines.

In code, spark dot read dot orc with the folder path. Print schema, show three rows.

Delta, the payments table. A delta table is a directory of parquet files plus a delta-log folder. Pass the path to the directory, and the transaction log handles the rest.

In code, spark dot read dot format, with the string delta, then dot load with the path. Print schema, show three rows.

Schema inference versus explicit.

Two paths to a schema, very different consequences.

Explicit schema is fast — no scan. Type safety is guaranteed. Null handling is declared per column. Recommended for production pipelines.

Inferred schema is slow — full or sampled scan. Type safety is best-effort guess. All columns are assumed nullable. Recommended for exploratory work only.

Inference triggers a separate scan over the data before your query starts running. On a one-hundred-gigabyte c-s-v, that is a non-trivial pre-job. Worse — a single malformed row can change the inferred type silently. Credit limit was a decimal yesterday. Today one row contains the string "N-A," and now the column is string, and downstream sum calls fail.

Always pass an explicit schema in production.

To make the difference visible, time the same c-s-v read twice — once with infer-schema set to true, once with the explicit customers schema declared earlier. The explicit version is faster, and the dtypes you print show the declared types in both cases — but only the explicit one was guaranteed.

Bad-record handling, the mode option.

When a row in your input does not conform to the schema, Spark needs a policy. The mode option takes one of three values.

Permissive — the default. The bad row's failed columns become null, and the row is kept. If you set the column-name-of-corrupt-record option, the raw bad string is stored in that column for later inspection.

Drop-malformed — silently drop the bad row.

Fail-fast — throw an exception on the first bad row.

Set the bad-records-path option to write rejected rows to a separate location for offline inspection — useful in production.

To see the difference, build a tiny c-s-v with one good row, one malformed row, and one more good row. The bad row has a non-numeric value in an integer column. Read it three times, once per mode. Permissive returns three rows, with the bad row's amount as null. Drop-malformed returns two rows, the bad row dropped. Fail-fast raises an exception on the first action — wrap it in a try-except so the cell still completes.

Reading multiple files, globs and directories.

A path that points at a directory reads every file under it. That is what every cell so far has done — the customers folder had multiple part-files inside, and Spark loaded them all.

For finer control, three options.

Glob patterns — like asterisk dot c-s-v, or part-asterisk dot parquet. Standard star and question-mark wildcards work.

Multiple paths — pass a list of paths to dot load, and Spark reads them all as one dataframe, as long as their schemas match.

The recursive-file-lookup option, set to true, descends into subdirectories instead of treating them as hive-style partitions.

In code, build a small directory tree under the write-examples folder. Two top-level c-s-v files with the same two-column schema, plus one nested c-s-v inside two extra subfolders. Then read it three ways. The glob form — asterisk dot c-s-v — picks up the two top-level files. The list-of-paths form names them explicitly — same answer. The recursive form reads everything under the directory, including the nested file. Each form returns a different row count, which is the proof.

Write modes.

Every df dot write call accepts a mode that controls what happens when the destination already exists.

Overwrite — replace existing data completely.

Append — add rows to existing data.

Ignore — do nothing if the destination exists, with no error.

Error — the default — raise an error if the destination exists.

The cells below use overwrite so they are idempotent. Re-running the notebook does not pile up duplicates.

Writing the five formats.

Same dataframe, written five ways. We pick a small slice — the first one hundred customers — so the file outputs stay manageable.

In code, take customers dot limit one hundred, then call write five times. C-s-v write with header set to true. JSON write. Parquet write. ORC write. And delta write via dot format dot save. Each write goes to its own subfolder under write examples. After all five, list each output folder and print the file count per format. The interesting thing is that the delta folder also contains a transaction log subfolder, while the other four are just data files plus a success marker.

Partition by, the partition-pruning win.

Partition by, with a column name, writes one subdirectory per distinct value of that column. A query that filters on that column reads only the relevant subdirectories — Spark never opens the rest. This is partition pruning, and it is the single biggest write-time decision for downstream read performance.

For example, if you partition card transactions by status, the output looks like three subfolders — status equals approved, status equals declined, status equals reversed — each with its own parquet files inside.

Pick a column with low cardinality — a few dozen distinct values at most. Partitioning by customer ID would create millions of tiny directories, which is much worse than no partitioning at all.

In code, write card transactions partitioned by status into a parquet folder. List the subdirectories — one per distinct status value. Then read it back with a filter on status equals approved. Spark skips the other partitions automatically. The row count returned is just the approved transactions.

Bucket by, bucketing for join-friendly layouts.

Bucket by, with a number and a column name, hashes rows into that number of files per partition, fixing the column's value-to-file mapping. Two reasons to use it.

Subsequent joins on that column can avoid a shuffle if both sides are bucketed identically — same bucket count, same key column.

Aggregations on the bucket column can run per-bucket without a network step.

The catch — bucket by only works with save as table. It needs the metastore to record the bucketing metadata. Plain save, with a path, ignores it.

In code, drop any existing card-transactions-bucketed table for idempotency. Then write card transactions with bucket by eight on card ID, sort by card ID, and save as table card transactions bucketed. A describe-formatted query then shows you the table location, the bucketing column, and the bucket count. Drop the table at the end to keep the catalog clean.

Save as table versus save, catalog versus filesystem.

Two write methods, very different downstream consequences.

Save with a path writes files. The result is a directory of files. The catalog has no record of them. To reload, you have to call spark dot read dot format dot load with the path again.

Save as table with a name writes files and registers the table in spark dot catalog. Once registered, you can call spark dot table with the name, or query it in SQL with select-star-from name.

Use save as table for SQL-style discoverability — anything anyone else might query. Use save for file-only outputs — intermediate staging, exports for downstream tools that do not read the catalog.

In code, write the same sample dataframe two ways. One write uses dot parquet to a file path. Another uses save as table to a catalog name. List the catalog tables — only the save-as-table target is there. Then read both. The path version reads via spark dot read dot parquet. The catalog version reads via spark dot table or via a SQL select. Drop the catalog table at the end.

Coalesce versus repartition before writing.

Both control the number of output files. The choice affects write speed, output file sizes, and downstream read parallelism.

Coalesce, with a number — no shuffle, narrow transformation. Fast. Output sizes can be uneven. Use it when you are reducing partition count and you do not need rebalancing.

Repartition, with a number — full shuffle, wide transformation. Slow. Output sizes are roughly equal. Use it when you are increasing partitions or rebalancing skewed data.

The classic case — df dot coalesce one dot write — to produce a single output file. Cheap, but if the upstream stage had wildly uneven partitions, the one output partition holds all of it.

In code, write the same sample dataframe two ways. Coalesce one dot write to one folder. Repartition four dot write to another. Count the part-files in each. The coalesce-one folder has one part-file; the repartition-four folder has four.

J-d-b-c briefly.

For relational sources — postgres, my-s-q-l, SQL server, oracle — Spark uses the j-d-b-c connector. The pattern: spark dot read dot format with j-d-b-c in quotes, then a chain of options. The options you always set are url — the j-d-b-c connection string — db-table or query, user, password, and driver — the j-d-b-c driver class.

For parallel reads, set four extra options that tell Spark how to slice the query into multiple concurrent connections. Partition column — a numeric or date column to slice on, ideally indexed in the source database for sanity. Lower bound and upper bound — the range of the partition column to cover. Num partitions — how many concurrent j-d-b-c connections to open.

Without those four, the read runs single-threaded. One connection pulls everything to one executor. Always set them on tables larger than a few hundred megabytes.

Writing is symmetric. Df dot write dot format with j-d-b-c, the same options, dot mode append, dot save.

A footnote on cloud paths. S-three-a colon-slash-slash bucket-name and beyond, abfss colon-slash-slash, g-s colon-slash-slash — all follow the exact same spark dot read dot format dot load pattern. Only the URL scheme differs. The format options stay identical.
